article.headline: Lafayette 47, Princeton 44
article.story: PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) -- Being down 13 points on the road in the second half isn't usually a recipe for success. But Lafayette coach Fran O'Hanlon was confident his senior-laden team would come back. "I thought we showed some real character tonight" O'Hanlon said. "We don't want to make a habit of it, but it shows our depth's better and that the guys are really making a commitment." Reserve Marcus Harley, a freshman guard, hit the key shot of the game, a 3-pointer from the right corner, to put the Leopards up for good with 3:19 left. Lafayette hung on to trip Princeton, 47-44, Monday night. It was the only shot Harley made but it put Lafayette ahead, 42-40. "He was a scorer in high school," said O'Hanlon, "and he's got a scorer's mentality. He has lots of confidence." Justin DeBerry scored nine of his team-high 13 points in the second half, including a driving layup with 2:12 left to make it 45-42. Princeton was led by Judson Wallace and Ed Persia, who each had 12 points. It was Lafayette's eighth straight win after an opening loss to Rutgers, while Princeton dropped its third straight to fall to 4-4. The 8-1 start is the best for Lafayette since the 1971-72 season. Princeton, which shot a season-low 29.8 percent from the field, still had a chance to win in the last two minutes. A blocked shot by Andre Logan led to a Persia layup that cut it to 45-44 with 1:06 remaining and a traveling violation gave Princeton a chance to take the lead with 29.8 seconds left. But after using most of the clock, Logan threw up an airball from the right side and Princeton had to foul Winston Davis, who grabbed the rebound. Davis, who had 11 points, hit both free throws to push the lead to three and Scott Greenman missed badly from long range to end the game. Princeton scored the first seven points of the second half to take its biggest lead at 29-16 with Persia converting the last five on a layup and a 3. But Lafayette came back with three straights 3's by DeBerry, Davis and Pat Betley to draw with four with 16:02 left. Princeton led, 22-16, at the half as both teams struggled with turnovers and poor shooting keeping the score low. The clubs combined for 21 turnovers and both shot under 40 percent from the field.
